data.chText: 中间；中部；中央；中心
data.enText: the part of sth that is at an equal distance from all its edges or sides; a point or a period of time between the beginning and the end of sth

data.chText: 中央有一个小岛的湖
data.enText: a lake with an island in the middle

data.chText: 他站在屋子的中间。
data.enText: He was standing in the middle of the room.

data.chText: 半夜里响起了电话铃声。
data.enText: The phone rang in the middle of the night.

data.chText: 这只鸡还没有熟透。
data.enText: This chicken isn't cooked in the middle.

data.chText: 他的照片就登在头版的正中央。
data.enText: His picture was right/bang (= exactly) in the middle of the front page.

data.chText: 拿出一张纸，在中间画一条线。
data.enText: Take a sheet of paper and draw a line down the middle .

data.chText: 我在这周过半的时候应该就能完成。
data.enText: I should have finished by the middle of the week.

data.chText: 腰部
data.enText: a person's waist

data.chText: 他拦腰抱住她。
data.enText: He grabbed her around the middle.
be in the middle of sth/of doing sth

data.chText: 忙于做
data.enText: to be busy doing sth

data.chText: 我打电话的时候，他们正在吃饭呢。
data.enText: They were in the middle of dinner when I called.

data.chText: 我正在写一封很难写的信。
data.enText: I'm in the middle of writing a difficult letter.
the middle of nowhere

data.chText: 偏远的地方
data.enText: a place that is a long way from other buildings, towns, etc.

data.chText: 她住在一个偏远的小农场。
data.enText: She lives on a small farm in the middle of nowhere.
split/divide sth down the middle

data.chText: 平分；分为相等的两半
data.enText: to divide sth into two equal parts

data.chText: 国内支持和反对罢工的人势均力敌。
data.enText: The country was split down the middle over the strike (= half supported it, half did not) .

data.chText: 中间的；中央的；居中的；正中的
data.enText: in a position in the middle of an object, group of objects, people, etc. between the beginning and the end of sth

data.chText: 钢笔在中间那个抽屉里。
data.enText: Pens are kept in the middle drawer.

data.chText: 三个孩子，她是老二。
data.enText: She's the middle child of three.

data.chText: 他在四十五六岁时很成功。
data.enText: He was very successful in his middle forties.

data.chText: 中等大小的房间
data.enText: a middle-sized room

data.chText: 社会中等收入阶层
data.enText: the middle-income groups in society
(steer, take, etc.) a middle course
(find, etc.) a/the middle way

data.chText: （走）中间道路；（取）中庸之道；（采取）折中办法
data.enText: (to take/find) an acceptable course of action that avoids two extreme positions

simple_means.memory_skill: mid 中间 + dle → 中间

ex.chText: 会议室中央有一张巨大的橡木桌子。
ex.enText: There is a huge oak table in the centre of the meeting room.

ex.chText: 北京是中国的政治和文化中心。
ex.enText: Beijing is the political and cultural centre of China.

synonyms.bx: 指空间、地域或物体的中心点，也可指学术、商业等活动的中心。

ex.chText: 去除果核，把苹果切成薄片。
ex.enText: Remove the cores, and thinly slice the apples.

ex.chText: 他们吁求的核心是言论自由。
ex.enText: The core of their appeal is freedom of speech.
Debt is at the core of the problem.

synonyms.bx: 指某物体的中心部分或某事物最重要的部分。

ex.chText: 我们必须抓住问题的核心。
ex.enText: We must get to the heart of the issue.

ex.chText: 他们去了市中心的一家大酒店。
ex.enText: They went to a big hotel in the heart/centre of the city.

synonyms.bx: 指事物最重要的部分；也可指方位上的中心，作此义解时可与 centre 换用。

ex.enText: There is a table in the middle of the parlor.
He came back home in the middle of the night.

synonyms.bx: 指空间、时间或事件的中间部分。

ex.chText: 我们在他的一群老朋友中找到了他。
ex.enText: We found him in the midst of a group of his usual friends.

ex.chText: 我在工作中趁隙休息了一个钟头。
ex.enText: In the midst of my work I snatched an hour's rest.

synonyms.bx: 指位于某地的中部或者处于一群人、一堆物品中间，也可指在某事的进行过程中。

tr: the middle area of the human torso (usually in front)
example: young American women believe that a bare midriff is fashionable
A whole is that which has beginning, middle, and end"- Aristotl

tr: an area that is approximately central within some larger region
example: it is in the center of town
they ran forward into the heart of the struggle
they were in the eye of the storm

tr: time between the beginning and the end of a temporal period
example: rain during the middle of April

tr: between an earlier and a later period of time
of a stage in the development of a language or literature between earlier and later stages
example: Middle English is the English language from about 1100 to 1500

tr: being neither at the beginning nor at the end in a series
example: adolescence is an awkward in-between age
the middle point on a line

value.def: The middle of something is the part of it that is furthest from its edges, ends, or outside surface.

example.ex: Howard stood in the middle of the room sipping a cup of coffee...
example.tran: 霍华德站在房间中央，小口抿着一杯咖啡。

example.ex: Hyde accelerated away from the kerb, swerving out into the middle of the street...
example.tran: 海德加速驶离路边，突然向街道中央一个急转弯。

example.ex: I was in the middle of the back row...
example.tran: 我在后排的中间。

example.ex: Make sure the roast potatoes aren't raw in the middle.
example.tran: 要确保这些烤土豆不夹生。

gramarinfo.label: usu <l>the</l> N in sing, oft N <l>of</l> n

value.def: The middle object in a row of objects is the one that has an equal number of objects on each side.

example.ex: The middle button of his uniform jacket was strained over his belly.
example.tran: 制服上装中间的纽扣在他的肚子上绷得紧紧的。

example.ex: ...the middle finger of her left hand.
example.tran: 她左手的中指

value.def: Your middle is the part of your body around your stomach.

example.ex: At age fifty-three, he now has a few extra pounds around his middle...
example.tran: 53岁的他腰间长了几磅赘肉。

example.ex: The cook's apron covered her middle.
example.tran: 厨用围裙裹着她的腰部。

value.def: The middle of an event or period of time is the part that comes after the first part and before the last part.

example.ex: I woke up in the middle of the night and could hear a tapping on the window...
example.tran: 我半夜里醒来，听见有敲窗户的声音。

example.ex: It was now the middle of November, cold and often foggy...
example.tran: 现在是11月中旬，天气寒冷而且经常有雾。

example.ex: By the middle of 1979, Jimmy Carter was in serious political trouble...
example.tran: 1979年中期，吉米·卡特陷入了严重的政治困境。

example.ex: She was born in the middle of a rain storm.
example.tran: 她出生在一场暴风雨中。

example.ex: The month began and ended quite dry, but the middle fortnight saw nearly 100mm of rain fall nationwide.
example.tran: 本月月初和月末颇为干燥， 不过中旬的两周全国有将近100毫米的降水。

value.def: If someone is in their middle thirties, for example, they are aged somewhere approximately between thirty-four and thirty-six.

example.ex: She knew he was in his middle fifties, although he looked much younger...
example.tran: 尽管他看上去年轻得多，她知道他在55岁左右。

example.ex: I went on competing till I was in my middle forties.
example.tran: 我继续参赛，直到45岁左右。

value.def: The middle child in a family has equal numbers of younger and older brothers and sisters.

example.ex: His middle son died in a drowning accident five years back.
example.tran: 他排行居中的那个儿子5年前意外溺水身亡。

value.tran: (兄弟姐妹中)年龄居中的，排行居中的

value.def: The middle course or way is a moderate course of action that lies between two opposite and extreme courses.

example.ex: He favoured a middle course between free enterprise and state intervention...
example.tran: 他更倾向于在自由经营与国家干预之间走一条中庸之道。

example.ex: The Mayor of Jerusalem has tried to minimise conflict by maintaining a middle way between the various religions.
example.tran: 耶路撒冷市市长对各宗教采取折中的态度，力图使冲突最小化。

value.tran: 折中的;中庸之道的;不走极端的

value.def: If you divide or split something down the middle, you divide or split it into two equal halves or groups.

example.ex: They agreed to split the bill down the middle...
example.tran: 他们同意均摊费用。

example.ex: If the conservatives are not removed, then the party will almost certainly split down the middle.
example.tran: 如果不除掉保守势力，那么这个党几乎肯定会分裂成两派。

value.def: If you are in the middle of doing something, you are busy doing it.

example.ex: It's a bit hectic. I'm in the middle of cooking for nine people...
example.tran: 我正忙着为9个人做饭呢，有点儿忙不过来。

example.ex: He was always in the middle of a business transaction.
example.tran: 他总是忙着做生意。
